54. Hyblaeis, a so-called ‘literary' or omamental epithet, Mount Hybla being famed for its honey. Cp. 5. 27; 10. 59 n. Here how- ever it seems to recall those associations with Sicilian pastoral which Virgil affects throughout the Bucolics. Cp. 2. 21 3 4. 1 ; 6. 1 ; 10. 1. florem depasta, lit. ‘having its flowers fed upon,' the pas- sive verb having a sort of middle force, common in Virgil, and borrowed from Greek usage.
